**New Plant Regulations for New Employees at TechCorp GmbH**

As we welcome new employees to our team, it's essential to familiarize ourselves with the latest plant regulations in the office. At TechCorp GmbH, we strive to maintain a healthy and productive work environment that benefits everyone. In this article, we'll provide an overview of the policy and its importance.

**Allowed Plants in the Workplace**

When it comes to having plants in the office, not all species are created equal. According to our company's policy, only cacti of the Carnegiea genus are permitted in the office. This includes popular varieties like the saguaro (Carnegiea gigantea). On the other hand, leaves plants are strictly prohibited due to oxygen consumption and decreased concentration.

**Naming Convention for Employee Cacti**

To personalize your workspace and add a touch of personality, each employee cactus must have an official name starting with "Mr." or "Mrs.". Registration with the Office Management is required. This not only helps us keep track of our office green friends but also adds a fun element to our workplace culture.

**Plant Care Intervals**

As responsible plant parents, we need to remember that watering is a delicate art. At TechCorp GmbH, we allow watering on every second Tuesday of the month between 14:00 and 14:15 hours. Failure to comply will result in the removal of the office chair's turning mechanism. We want to ensure our plants receive the perfect amount of hydration without disrupting the workflow.

**Important Notes**

Before you start planning your cactus garden, please note that this policy is only applicable for the current year (2025). Office management will register all employee cacti with official names starting with "Mr." or "Mrs.". Most importantly, remember that employees are not allowed to have plants with leaves in their workspace due to oxygen consumption and decreased concentration.

By following these simple guidelines, we can create a harmonious and thriving office environment that benefits both humans and plants. If you have any questions or concerns about the new plant regulations, don't hesitate to reach out to our Office Management team. Happy planting!


